link_check.notes: can find it by repeating a search of only the article title, perhaps the 'special section' bit broke the search
granularity mismatch, record is for full issue of journal while PRL only has article-level records

We have access to this journal vai two subscriptions but neither contain 2019 issues, which this article is in. I think the problem with this link is actually how Summon implements its "Full Text Online" facet; we have this article in print, and the link goes to our catalog where you can find the print issue, but we do not have it online.

Seems like this journal's website moved, the domain cannot be found but if I Google search I can find a new site with an issue index. The link to download the needed issue fails (it points to the same dead domain) but I can from there go to the publishers site where the issue is available for free. It's certainly not trivial to find.
Seems like a knowledbgebase error, we land on the right page but do not have access to this particular edition of the ebook (our subscription does have access to a different edition).
Land on journal home page, can navigate to the issue & find article within it.
Land on the journal index, can navigate to issue & then article.
An acronym written with periods in the article title (E.G.) was written only with letters in the database query (EG) which fails; merely adding the deleted periods causes the query to succeed.

We do have access to this article but you can't get there from the weird "Document Unavailable" screen from PRL which I've never seen before. The title in the database is wildly different from the Summon index, which seems to be completely improvised. It's definitely talking about the same article but the words in no way align with anything like a title in the source.
Just cannot find this article, even when limiting to the publication.

A questionable oneâ€”we end up on some kind of metadata summary page, none of the book's content in site, but can get to that by clicking its publication date. This seems like there either shouldn't be a title-link record for the ebook (it's an anthology of sorts) or the link should go somewhere more useful.

The db query shows 78 articles with this same, generic title. You can eventually find the specific one being referenced but it takes time. If the query included something like publication date then it'd be much more successful.
Similar to last one, a db query with an incredibly generic title yields way too many results, this time 1,549. You can find the right one by modifying the query to be more specific.
Link goes to catalog record, we do have this issue in print.
You can make the query broader by removing what Summon thinks the title is, then backtrack from the issue's articles to this specific one.
You land on a journal home page instead of the article, the journal was made OA in 2012 but this article is older than that and it not accessible in the public back issues.

You can make the query less specific, it's choking on the title as usual, then drill down from the issue's list of articles to find this specific one. The title is pretty much the same as the one in the Summon index but the query is constructed to fail if the titles aren't identical.
You land on a journal home page instead of the article, the journal was made OA in 2012 but this article is older than that and it not accessible in the public back issues.
We don't have this title online, only in print.
A laughably vague headline query yields over a thousand results. Creating a more specific query lets you find the article.
Cannot find an article with anything like this title in the publishing newspaper.
Cannot find an article with a similar title in the publishing newspaper.

This is literally a Hathi Trust ebook for which Summon knows the URL but chooses not to use it, inexplicably directing us on a wild Google chase through EBSCOhost. I landed initially on a screen asking me to choose between 'EBSCOhost Research Databases' and 'ccAdvisor' (perhaps another resource that we subscribe to?) and when I select EBSCOhost I'm asked to choose which database(s) I want to search within. If I continue with the default selection (Art & Architecture Source as well as Avery Index to Architectural Periodicals) then search the full title, I can find two book reviews of the title but not the title itself.
You end up with two very similar articles matching the db query, one of them is correct.
If you just broaden the db query you can find the article.
We have this journal in print only.
Article seems similar to some AP articles you can find but I cannot locate it in the listed newspaper.
Article title searches within the publication fail.
I can find article's containing the name in the title but nothing that looks quite like this one.
Article is there under this issue but with a different title, takes a while to find.

I tried editing the title several times but couldn't get this OpenURL form to find the article. Chances are, if the Summon link had landed inside a database, I could actually find the article, but it instead dies on an unfriendly OpenURL form and there's not a lot of metadata correction you can do to try to get it to work.
Our online coverage for this title doesn't go back as far as this article.
Summon has the title in form "{English version}/{Spanish version}" while the source article appears to be only in English. If you remove the Spanish version of the title the db query resolves.
You land on the home page of this open access journal and not the specific article, but you can navigate to it.
You land on the journal home page and can navigate to this specific article, though it's a bit tricky and you can't actually read it until you create an account with the publisher.
Perhaps an apostrophe in the title throws the query off but you're able to find the article by editing it.
I can find this article in this publication (it's OA) but not in the database, it's possible it's some online-only content and the db has only the print issues of the journal.

It may be possible to track down this book review but I spent a good 5-10 minutes and couldn't based on my starting point. You end up in our library catalog looking at the print record for the journal, clicking a link that eventually takes you through EBSCOhost proves fruitless as you can easily find reviews of the title in other journals but not this particular one, at least not after I tried several search variations.
There are 15 results to the query and you can find the correct one within them.
Identical problem to the last one: 15 search results of which only one is right.
We only have this publication in print.
Granularity mismatch: Summon index has name of specific review while PRL lumps together several reviews under a topical heading.
Doesn't even look like this publication is contained within Nexis Uni.
While you can technically edit the article title to "[Book Reviews]" to get this OpenURL to resolve, it's near impossible to know that that's the right thing to do.

Link goes to Springer but we don't subscribe to any Springer packages, perhaps the article is being mistaken for OA but its record doesn't indicate as such. This one just shouldn't be showing up in our results at all.
Granularity mismatch: Summon index lists the title of the book being reviewed while PRL has it as part of a "Books in brief" larger article.
You land on a sort of metadata page for a larger work with no tools to get you to the specific section you want.
You can fix the query by making it broader, it's formatted as a title query for "{book title} by {author} review" but a keyword search on simply "{book title}" within the issue works.
You land on a journal index page and can browse to the desired article from there.
You land on a journal index page and can browse to the desired article from there.

You land on a journal home page with a "search for articles within this journal" input; if you paste in the article's title, it comes right up. Not sure why the link isn't just to the aritcle when others seem to be for this journal.

Various searches on the article title do not yield anything. This is an OA article; you can find its DOI via PubMed & the DOI goes straight to the full PDF. Inexplicable that it's not included in PRL.
This source is one of three poems, printed on consecutive pages, from the same author. The first and last poems appear; this one is in between them and not listed on the database, it's just missing.

Summon index has the correct (all Spanish) title while the database inexplicably translates only the subtitle, causing the query to break. You can find the article by removing the title part of the query to find all articles in the issues then locating the desired result.
We not only have this article in an EBSCO database but it's also OA, you can find both copies by browsing but Summon drops you on EBSCO's OpenURL form which is hopeless.
You're taken to the journal home page but can browse to the correct issue and find the article within it.
Same situation as last. You're taken to the journal home page but can browse to the correct issue and find the article within it.

As with an earlier article, we have this via EBSCO and it's OA but the EBSCO OpenURL page you land on won't let you get to it. I suspect an issue with translation or accented characters is what's causing the problem but couldn't diagnose it given a few minutes.

This is a duplicate of an earlier search result so the article does exist in EBSCO & as OA but the Summon link to the journal's OJS instance appears to be malformed, it goes to a "file not found" error.
As with the last article, this one is available via EBSCO and as OA but Summon's link is malformed.
We're taken to a list of hundreds of articles in the journal, none of which appear to be this one. Cannot find this one even with repeated search attempts from various angles.
Taken to 3 results with the same title from the same publication, limiting the query by an additional measure like publication date would've retrieved the correct one.
Same as last: taken to 3 results with the same title from the same publication, limiting the query by an additional measure like publication date would've retrieved the correct one.
Same as 2 other results: taken to 3 results with the same title from the same publication, limiting the query by an additional measure like publication date would've retrieved the correct one.

You can edit the broken query in PRL by making it less specific. This is a typical problem with book reviews; the Summon index has chosen to include the author of the work being reviewed in the title while the destination database does not include their name, causing a disconnect between the two.
Exactly the same problem as the last book review: Summon index includes an author name in title, PRL does not, the overly-specific query causes a disconnect.
Third in a row with the same problem: author name included in title in Summon index, not included in title in PRL, query linking the too is constructed with too many specifics.
Taken to "document unavailable" screen in PRL, which tends to mean they know the document exists but do not have access to it.
Granularity mismatch: PRL has this article under a larger section with other pieces. If you correct the PRL query to use start page instead of title it works.
The results show 4 basically identical articles including the desired one.
Two identical looking results are presented, they're both the intended article.
I don't even think this publication is included in this database.
You can correct the query, making it broader, to retrieve the article.
Desired results is listed among four others, just have to scroll to it.
You can replace the title in the query with start page to find this resource review.

It's hopeless going from EBSCO's OpenURL to the full text. We're supposed to have full text coverage for this title but this particular issue looks like only citations, plus I can't find the article in the issue.
PRL's "document unavailable" screen.
Replacing the title with the starting page in the query causes it to succeed.

Repeated searches don't yield this article even though the metadata looks correct. I don't think this journal is in this particular database, though we have it in two others where the full text can be found, so this is just a profoundly misguided decision on Summon's part.
I'm not sure why this one is in our results, it's an ebook, not OA, and not in anything we subscribe to as far as I can tell.

Again the query constructed in the destination database is too specific and doesn't exactly match the index. It's a Nexis Uni HEADLINE() query but Nexis includes a subtitle of sorts in its headline so the link breaks. Editing the query to be more general causes it to pull up the desired result first in a list of results.

I tried editing the Nexis Uni query several ways but couldn't retrieve the desired result. The query in the destination database was for a generic phrase and lacked the subtitle which provided the appropriate context, causing a single completely irrelevant result about football to appear. It would be incredibly difficult for an inexperienced researcher to realize what's happening here and get to the full text.

The link goes to the home page of the journal but not the individual article. One must backtrack to the issues index, find the appropriate one, then locate the article within it. It wasn't that hard for me but it took a minute to figure out where to go from the home page since it happened to show the latest issue which had an identical issue number to the one I was looking for.

The constructed OpenURL query uses the wrong family name for the author, who has four total names. This looks very much like poorly thought out Western bias in constructing an OpenURL. It's easy to find the article if you search for its full title or if you just use the proper name in the OpenURL.
Same article & issue as #5 out of these documents; you land on the journal's home page and not the specific article, takes a bit of navigation to get there.
You're taken to the journal's home page and not the article itself. One can navigate to it by finding the correct issue and then selecting the article from the issue's table of contents.
Editing the very long HEADLINE() query to be more generic still fails to retrieve this article despite numerous attempts.

You're taken to the EBSCOhost/ccAdvisor screen, if you choose EBSCOhost then continue with the default databases selected then search for the book title and author, its contents appear as a list of records for each chapter. This is a lot of steps and I wouldn't expect many novice researchers to complete them successfully.
The article is the ninth result listed after a bunch of similar titles. It would be hard to know which one was the correct result without paying close attention.

I'm able to find a citation for this article in an EBSCO database but not the full text. Since you land on EBSCO's OpenURL resolver, which doesn't consider citation-only records when trying to resolve links, I suspect the issue is that the Summon index thinks EBSCO has full text for this publication while it in fact does not.

Another overly-specific Nexis Uni query that breaks. It's a HEADLINE() query starting with "BRIEF:" which is not what Nexis has in the title. If you make it a generic query for the article title minus the BRIEF prefix then it pulls up the relevant result first.

An overly-specific HEADLINE() query fails to resolve to the target in Nexis Uni. A "YYYY/YYYY" date range in the article's title had it's middle forward-slash removed, that likely contributed to the query breaking, but again a less specific query is able to retrieve the article.
Same situation as last article: too specific Nexis Uni query is slightly malformed, editing it a little bit to a more generic query yields the desired result.

I tried editing the Nexis Uni query several ways but could not retrieve what looks like an obit. It's possible that the Nexis Uni subscription for this resource (a local newspaper of a major American city) does not include the obituary section.

This article is a list of obituaries, the Summon index has its title as a list of names while PRL lists it simply as "Obituaries". If you delete the TI() (title) portion of the PRL query you can find it in the results if you know what you're looking for. The Summon record contains a link to an open access version that resolves perfectly.

It is pretty easy to get to the full text; you land on a table of contents for an ebook and the desired resource is one of the chapters, which is linked. Still, you have to scroll some and you're not taken directly to the chapter so I count this as a broken link.
